classes = ['bald_eagle', 'elk', 'racoon', 'raven']
# class_dict = {'bald_eagle':0, 'elk':1, 'racoon':2, 'raven':3}
path_train = 'drive/MyDrive/CA5_dataset/train'
path_test = 'drive/MyDrive/CA5_dataset/test'
paths = {'train':[], 'test':[]}
train_labels, test_labels = [], []

for c in classes:
    path = path_train + '/' + c
    for img in os.listdir(path):
        paths['train'].append(os.path.join(path, img))
        train_labels.append(c)
        
for c in classes:
    path = path_test + '/' + c
    for img in os.listdir(path):
        paths['test'].append(os.path.join(path, img))
        test_labels.append(c)
In [ ]:
traindf = pd.DataFrame({'image':paths['train'], 'label': train_labels})
testdf = pd.DataFrame({'image':paths['test'], 'label': test_labels})

Optimizers:¶

Momentum:¶

Momentum is a widely-used strategy for accelerating the convergence of gradient-based optimization techniques.

Momentum is an average of gradients that changes during the time and we use it to update weight in each step. Therefore, it leads to faster convergence.

Normally, the updates to weights are product of learning rate and the gradiant of error/loss. But if we use momentum, we add a new term. For each new weight update, we add the product of momentum value and the previous update. So the previous updates are considered on each. Because of this one batch can't change the direction of descent if most of the previous batchs were moving toward a direction.

Using momentum the learning will happen faster as we will have bigger updates. It can also help us to skip the local minima because of the big update.

  • A very large momentum can cause random behavior and prevent converging. Thus, it can stop the learning proccess. And a very small value won't help up much.

Epochs:¶

  • the most common method for training in deep learning is a form of gradient descent. Each epoch finds the approximate direction that each parameter needs to be adjusted but it's just approximate. If you adjust too much in one epoch you will overshoot the set of parameters you're actually trying to find.

  • We may not be able to have a lot of new data to train the model on, so we use the same data in multiple epochs to learn its features. But if we have enough data we may get the optimal result in one iteration.

  • If we set the number of epochs to a very large number, it may lead to have and overfitted model, because we train the data for many times and our model will start to model the noises in our data and it is a sign of overfitting and the accuracy of the test data will be reduced.

  • Early stopping: To prevent overfitting, we can use early-stopping techniques. It means we stop the learning process when the it evaluation data results start to worsening.

Loss Function:¶

  • Cross-entropy is prefered for classification, while mean squared error(MSE) is one of the best choices for regression. This comes directly from the statement of the problems itself - in classification you work with very particular set of possible output values thus MSE is badly defined (as it does not have this kind of knowledge thus penalizes errors in incompatible way).

Regularization:¶

A neural network has the tendency to memorize its training. In such cases, the network fails catastrophically when subjected to the test data. This is the classic case of the network failing to generalize.

  • Using L2 method, in each update to weight, we add a product of constant and the previous weight. This constant is predefined and independent of the learning process, so this change to weight, keeps the model from overfitting.
In [80]:

model.add(layers.Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

Dropout:¶

  • The idea of dropout is simple. Given a dropout rate, the Dropout layer randomly removes that fraction of units from participating in the next layer. The Dropout layer makes neural networks robust to unforeseen input data because the network is trained to predict correctly, even if some units are missing. It's worth noting that dropout is not used in the output layer and it is only active during training. Moreover, dropout is not present during predictions.
In [85]:
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Input(shape=(100, 100, 1)))
model.add(layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
model.add(layers.Dense(4, activation='softmax'))
model.compile(
    loss='categorical_crossentropy', 
    optimizer='Adam', 
    metrics=['accuracy']
)
model.summary()
